<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="421" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[159,772,1179,2019]" box="[159,262,1179,1205]" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">
<emphasis box="[159,262,1179,1205]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[159,772,1179,2019]" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">
In our study area, the 
<emphasis box="[457,626,1213,1239]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis-</emphasis>
like bats exhibit two distinct morphological forms. One has ears with a straight or slightly notched posterior edge, and has a larger body size; the ears of the other morph have a curved margin to the posterior edge and body size is smaller (
<tableCitation box="[462,554,1383,1409]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="10.[99,112,501,522]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements of nine external traits of 52 bat species. FA — forearm length, BM — body mass, HB — head and body length, TL — tail length, TB — tibia length, HF — hind foot length, TU — thumb length: EL — ear length, TR — tragus length. Numbers denote minimum and maximum, and sample size; values in parentheses indicate measurements of specimens of this study; ‘ – ’: data not available. BMs for specimens were taken in the field. All measurements in mm, except for BM (in g)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" tableUuid="1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The two morphs also differed in habitat use; whereas the larger morph was usually abundant in disturbed habitats but rare within forested habitats, the capture rate of the small morph was generally high in all surveyed habitats. Notably, in contrast to the irritable and noisy behaviors of other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1824" box="[530,665,1586,1612]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[530,665,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Cynopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, most individuals of the small 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1824" box="[561,696,1620,1646]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[561,696,1620,1646]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Cynopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were generally calm and silent either in nets or during processing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[159,772,1179,2019]" lastBlockId="8.[816,1429,223,2019]" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[197,496,1721,1747]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Campbell" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="764 - 781" refId="ref24993" refString="CAMPBELL, P., C. J. SCHNEIDER, A. M. ADNAN, A. ZUBAID, and T. H. KUNZ. 2004. Phylogeny and phylogeography of Old World fruit bats in the Cynopterus brachyotis complex. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 33: 764 - 781." type="journal article" year="2004">
Campbell 
<emphasis box="[330,400,1721,1747]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
described five cytochrome 
<emphasis box="[263,278,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">b</emphasis>
lineages of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[447,615,1755,1781]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[447,615,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex in South and Southeast Asia, two of which were from the Sunda Shelf and described as Forest and Sunda lineages. The two Sunda Shelf 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[595,772,1857,1883]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[595,772,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lineages also differ in body size and habitat use; 
<taxonomicName authority="Forest" authorityName="Forest" box="[159,403,1925,1951]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[159,320,1925,1951]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
Forest
</taxonomicName>
lineage has a smaller forearm length (FA = 
<quantity box="[345,528,1959,1985]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" metricValueMax="6.37" metricValueMin="5.43" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="59.0" valueMax="63.7" valueMin="54.3">54.3–63.7 mm</quantity>
) and is associated with forest, contrasting with the larger 
<taxonomicName authority="Sunda" authorityName="Sunda" box="[613,889,223,2019]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[613,771,1993,2019]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
Sunda
</taxonomicName>
lineage (FA = 60.0–70.0 mm) associated with disturbed habitats. Nevertheless, the authors did not assign either to 
<taxonomicName box="[1021,1186,291,317]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[1021,1186,291,317]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because they were not able to make comparisons with type material (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[824,1101,359,385]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Campbell" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="764 - 781" refId="ref24993" refString="CAMPBELL, P., C. J. SCHNEIDER, A. M. ADNAN, A. ZUBAID, and T. H. KUNZ. 2004. Phylogeny and phylogeography of Old World fruit bats in the Cynopterus brachyotis complex. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 33: 764 - 781." type="journal article" year="2004">
Campbell 
<emphasis box="[953,1017,359,385]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
). Three following publications (
<bibRefCitation author="ABDULLAH, M. T. &amp; V. K. JAYARAJ" box="[895,1241,393,419]" journalOrPublisher="The Sarawak Museum Journal" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="223 - 236" part="62" refId="ref24958" refString="ABDULLAH, M. T., and V. K. JAYARAJ. 2006. Preliminary investigation on the relationship of the nominate C. brachyotis with the small-sized and large-sized C. brachyotis using clustering analysis. The Sarawak Museum Journal, 62: 223 - 236" title="Preliminary investigation on the relationship of the nominate C. brachyotis with the small-sized and large-sized C. brachyotis using clustering analysis" type="journal article" year="2006">Abdullah and Jayaraj, 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jayaraj" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Jayaraj" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="259 - 271" refId="ref26466" refString="JAYARAJ, V. K., C. J. LAMAN, and M. T. ABDULLAH. 2012. A predictive model to differentiate the fruit bats Cynopterus brachyotis and C. cf. brachyotis forest (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Malaysia using multivariate analysis. Zoological Studies, 51: 259 - 271." type="journal article" year="2012">
Jayaraj 
<emphasis box="[1356,1421,393,419]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fong" box="[893,1099,427,453]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Fong" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="225 - 248" refId="ref25480" refString="FONG, P. H., E. YUZINE, and M. T. ABDULLAH. 2013. Genetic variations and population structure of the genus Cynopterus in Malaysia. Pertanika Journal of Tropical Agricultural Science, 36: 225 - 248." type="journal article" year="2013">
Fong 
<emphasis box="[962,1023,427,453]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2013
</bibRefCitation>
) confirmed the presence of two distinct morphs of ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[1110,1271,461,487]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[1110,1271,461,487]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ in 
<collectingCountry box="[1321,1429,461,487]" name="Malaysia" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
and their ecological preferences in habitat. By a preliminary morphological comparison with the 
<typeStatus pageId="8" pageNumber="419">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority=", Abdullah and Jayaraj (2006)" authorityName=", Abdullah and Jayaraj" authorityYear="2006" box="[911,1429,563,589]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[911,1071,563,589]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ABDULLAH, M. T. &amp; V. K. JAYARAJ" box="[1087,1429,563,589]" journalOrPublisher="The Sarawak Museum Journal" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="223 - 236" part="62" refId="ref24958" refString="ABDULLAH, M. T., and V. K. JAYARAJ. 2006. Preliminary investigation on the relationship of the nominate C. brachyotis with the small-sized and large-sized C. brachyotis using clustering analysis. The Sarawak Museum Journal, 62: 223 - 236" title="Preliminary investigation on the relationship of the nominate C. brachyotis with the small-sized and large-sized C. brachyotis using clustering analysis" type="journal article" year="2006">Abdullah and Jayaraj (2006)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
further suggested that Malaysia’s large morph was the nominate species and the small form is a different species. Interestingly, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[1141,1275,665,691]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1141,1275,665,691]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was first described from the Mentawai Islands off the west coast of Sumatra, is similar in body size to the small forest 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Abdullah and Jayaraj" authorityYear="2006" box="[975,1140,767,793]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[975,1140,767,793]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[1192,1303,767,793]" name="Malaysia" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Cynopterus minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is commonly found on all the Greater Sunda Islands and is frequently sympatric with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi, 1991)" baseAuthorityName="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" baseAuthorityYear="1991" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[816,983,869,895]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" firstAuthor="Kitchener" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="307 - 363" refId="ref26968" refString="KITCHENER, D. J., and I. MAHARADATUNKAMSI. 1991. Description of a new species of Cynopterus (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Nusa Tenggara Indonesia. Records of the Western Australian Museum, 15: 307 - 363." type="journal article" year="1991">Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi, 1991</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike the two Malaysian lineages, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" firstAuthor="Kitchener" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="307 - 363" refId="ref26968" refString="KITCHENER, D. J., and I. MAHARADATUNKAMSI. 1991. Description of a new species of Cynopterus (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Nusa Tenggara Indonesia. Records of the Western Australian Museum, 15: 307 - 363." type="journal article" year="1991">Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi (1991)</bibRefCitation>
reported overlap in radius length of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[1157,1290,972,998]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1157,1290,972,998]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.74" metricValueMax="6.1899999999999995" metricValueMin="5.29" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="57.4" valueMax="61.9" valueMin="52.9">52.9–61.9 mm</quantity>
) and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[941,1106,1006,1032]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[941,1106,1006,1032]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[1127,1308,1006,1032]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.07" metricValueMax="6.67" metricValueMin="5.47" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="60.7" valueMax="66.7" valueMin="54.7">54.7–66.7 mm</quantity>
) in 
<collectingCountry name="Indonesia" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
. However, the authors included juveniles and subadults in their samples (
<bibRefCitation author="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" firstAuthor="Kitchener" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="307 - 363" refId="ref26968" refString="KITCHENER, D. J., and I. MAHARADATUNKAMSI. 1991. Description of a new species of Cynopterus (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Nusa Tenggara Indonesia. Records of the Western Australian Museum, 15: 307 - 363." type="journal article" year="1991">Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi, 1991</bibRefCitation>
), which may have smaller forearm lengths (
<bibRefCitation author="Elangovan" box="[985,1281,1142,1168]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Elangovan" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="107 - 116" refId="ref25394" refString="ELANGOVAN, V., E. Y. S. PRIYA, H. RAGHURAM, and G. MARIMUTHU. 2003. Postnatal development in the Indian short-nosed fruit bat Cynopterus sphinx: growth rate and age estimation. Acta Chiropterologica, 5: 107 - 116." type="journal article" year="2003">
Elangovan 
<emphasis box="[1128,1195,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2003
</bibRefCitation>
). The taxonomic relationship between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[1178,1316,1176,1202]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1178,1316,1176,1202]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the small forest 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[963,1122,1210,1236]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[963,1122,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains unclear.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[816,1429,223,2019]" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">
Given the above, we regard the two morphs of 
<emphasis box="[816,993,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis-</emphasis>
like bats in our study as different species, and assign the large morph to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[1270,1429,1312,1338]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[1270,1429,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authority="Sunda in Campbell et al., 2004" authorityName="Sunda in Campbell" authorityYear="2004" box="[861,1417,1346,1372]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[861,1022,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
Sunda in 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[1149,1417,1346,1372]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Campbell" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="764 - 781" refId="ref24993" refString="CAMPBELL, P., C. J. SCHNEIDER, A. M. ADNAN, A. ZUBAID, and T. H. KUNZ. 2004. Phylogeny and phylogeography of Old World fruit bats in the Cynopterus brachyotis complex. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 33: 764 - 781." type="journal article" year="2004">
Campbell 
<emphasis box="[1274,1335,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
). Our samples of the small round-eared 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1824" box="[1293,1428,1380,1406]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1428,1380,1406]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Cynopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are comparable in forearm length (
<quantity box="[1245,1425,1414,1440]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.904999999999999" metricValueMax="6.16" metricValueMin="5.65" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="59.05" valueMax="61.6" valueMin="56.5">56.5–61.6 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[816,834,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">x</emphasis>
= 
<quantity box="[879,988,1448,1474]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.72" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="57.2">57.2 mm</quantity>
) to both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[1100,1229,1448,1474]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1100,1229,1448,1474]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[1247,1425,1448,1474]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.74" metricValueMax="6.1899999999999995" metricValueMin="5.29" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="57.4" valueMax="61.9" valueMin="52.9">52.9–61.9 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[816,834,1481,1507]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">x</emphasis>
= 
<quantity box="[880,987,1482,1508]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.75" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="57.5">57.5 mm</quantity>
— 
<bibRefCitation author="Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi" firstAuthor="Kitchener" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="307 - 363" refId="ref26968" refString="KITCHENER, D. J., and I. MAHARADATUNKAMSI. 1991. Description of a new species of Cynopterus (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Nusa Tenggara Indonesia. Records of the Western Australian Museum, 15: 307 - 363." type="journal article" year="1991">Kitchener and Maharadatunkamsi, 1991</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Forest" authorityName="Forest" box="[984,1228,1516,1542]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[984,1145,1516,1542]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
Forest
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[1247,1425,1516,1542]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" metricValueMax="6.37" metricValueMin="5.43" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="59.0" valueMax="63.7" valueMin="54.3">54.3–63.7 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[816,834,1549,1575]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">x</emphasis>
= 
<quantity box="[877,983,1550,1576]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.81" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="58.1">58.1 mm</quantity>
— 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[1029,1291,1550,1576]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Campbell" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="764 - 781" refId="ref24993" refString="CAMPBELL, P., C. J. SCHNEIDER, A. M. ADNAN, A. ZUBAID, and T. H. KUNZ. 2004. Phylogeny and phylogeography of Old World fruit bats in the Cynopterus brachyotis complex. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 33: 764 - 781." type="journal article" year="2004">
Campbell 
<emphasis box="[1152,1212,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName authority="Forest" authorityName="Forest" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[1363,1390,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[816,940,1584,1610]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">brachyotis</emphasis>
Forest
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jayaraj" box="[1044,1285,1584,1610]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Jayaraj" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="259 - 271" refId="ref26466" refString="JAYARAJ, V. K., C. J. LAMAN, and M. T. ABDULLAH. 2012. A predictive model to differentiate the fruit bats Cynopterus brachyotis and C. cf. brachyotis forest (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Malaysia using multivariate analysis. Zoological Studies, 51: 259 - 271." type="journal article" year="2012">
Jayaraj 
<emphasis box="[1140,1203,1584,1610]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). Similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[816,950,1618,1644]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[816,950,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in using both primary forest and disturbed habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" box="[1006,1158,1652,1678]" firstAuthor="IUCN" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" refId="ref26437" refString="IUCN 2013. IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2013.1. &lt;www. iucnredlist. org&gt;. Last accessed on 4 th July 2013." type="book" year="2013">IUCN, 2013</bibRefCitation>
), the small 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1824" box="[1293,1428,1652,1678]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1428,1652,1678]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Cynopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from BBSL is also a habitat generalist, which differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Forest" authorityName="Forest" box="[894,1170,1720,1746]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[894,1071,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
Forest
</taxonomicName>
, a forest specialist (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[824,1085,1754,1780]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Campbell" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="764 - 781" refId="ref24993" refString="CAMPBELL, P., C. J. SCHNEIDER, A. M. ADNAN, A. ZUBAID, and T. H. KUNZ. 2004. Phylogeny and phylogeography of Old World fruit bats in the Cynopterus brachyotis complex. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 33: 764 - 781." type="journal article" year="2004">
Campbell 
<emphasis box="[948,1008,1754,1780]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="ABDULLAH, M. T. &amp; V. K. JAYARAJ" box="[1096,1424,1754,1780]" journalOrPublisher="The Sarawak Museum Journal" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="223 - 236" part="62" refId="ref24958" refString="ABDULLAH, M. T., and V. K. JAYARAJ. 2006. Preliminary investigation on the relationship of the nominate C. brachyotis with the small-sized and large-sized C. brachyotis using clustering analysis. The Sarawak Museum Journal, 62: 223 - 236" title="Preliminary investigation on the relationship of the nominate C. brachyotis with the small-sized and large-sized C. brachyotis using clustering analysis" type="journal article" year="2006">Abdullah and Jayaraj, 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jayaraj" box="[816,1051,1788,1814]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Jayaraj" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" pagination="259 - 271" refId="ref26466" refString="JAYARAJ, V. K., C. J. LAMAN, and M. T. ABDULLAH. 2012. A predictive model to differentiate the fruit bats Cynopterus brachyotis and C. cf. brachyotis forest (Chiroptera: Pteropodidae) from Malaysia using multivariate analysis. Zoological Studies, 51: 259 - 271." type="journal article" year="2012">
Jayaraj 
<emphasis box="[909,970,1788,1814]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">et al.</emphasis>
, 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). Although the previous studies do not provide for comparisons of behavior and ear shape in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[961,1088,1856,1882]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[961,1088,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Forest" authorityName="Forest" box="[1143,1383,1856,1882]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[1143,1301,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
Forest
</taxonomicName>
, we tentatively regard the small form as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1906" box="[1293,1429,1890,1916]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1429,1890,1916]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">C. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on similarities of body size and habitat use.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[816,1429,223,2019]" lastBlockId="9.[159,771,223,518]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="421" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicName box="[854,1136,1959,1985]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="419" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[854,1136,1959,1985]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="419">Cynopterus brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(the large form) was the most abundant pteropodid species in the study area. Capture rates were usually high in coffee plantations, forest edges and river habitats but low within forests. In our study area, 
<taxonomicName box="[560,721,290,316]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[560,721,290,316]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vahl" baseAuthorityYear="1797" box="[447,566,324,350]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sphinx">
<emphasis box="[447,566,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. sphinx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by shorter ears (&lt;18.0 mm in 
<taxonomicName box="[360,524,357,383]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[360,524,357,383]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and&gt; 18.0 mm in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vahl" baseAuthorityYear="1797" box="[159,270,391,417]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sphinx">
<emphasis box="[159,270,391,417]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. sphinx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[402,558,391,417]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="horsfieldii">
<emphasis box="[402,558,391,417]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. horsfieldii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of peg-like cusps on the lower cheek teeth and ear shape (straight or slightly notched at posterior edge in 
<taxonomicName box="[189,348,492,518]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Cynopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachyotis">
<emphasis box="[189,348,492,518]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. brachyotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, strongly notched in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[599,754,492,518]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="421" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="horsfieldii">
<emphasis box="[599,754,492,518]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="421">C. horsfieldii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
